Denote by $P(x,y)$ be the functional equation.
It is easy to check that $f(x) = 0\,\forall x$ solves it. Assume that this isn't the required function. Let $a=f(0)$. Then, $P(0, 0)$ gives us $f(a)=a$. 
Denote $f(a)=a$ as $Q(a,\text{True})$. $P(x,0)$ then gives us
\begin{align}
f(f(x)) = f(x)f(0)-f(x)+f(0)=f(x)(a-1)+a
\end{align}
And plugging this back in $Q(a,\text{True})$ gives us
\begin{align}
a=f(f(a))=f(a)(a-1)+a=(a-1)a+a=0\implies a=2
\end{align}
Thus, we have that $f(0) = 2$. $f(0)f(0)=f(f(0))+f(0)-k \cdot 0 \implies 4=2+k \implies k=2$ and thus, $f(1)=k=2$.
</think> <answer>2</answer>

