To solve this, we first let the repeating decimal be $x$, i.e.
\begin{equation}x=1.\overline{234}.\end{equation}
As in the definition of a repeating decimal, we have
\begin{equation}1000x=1234.\overline{234}.\end{equation}
We then subtract $x-1000x$, which gives
\begin{equation}999x=1233.\end{equation}
Hence,
\begin{equation}x=\frac{1233}{999}.\end{equation}
But, this fraction is improper. Thus, we find the greatest common divisor (GCD) of 1233 and 999. It is 3.
\begin{equation}\frac{1233\div 3}{999\div 3}=\frac{411}{333}.\end{equation}
Finally, we simplify the fraction
\begin{equation}\frac{411\div 3}{333\div 3}=\frac{137}{111}.\end{equation}
So,
\begin{equation}1.\overline{234}=\boxed{\frac{137}{111}}.\end{equation}</think> <answer> \boxed{\frac{137}{111}} </answer>
